# OpenShift GitOps Context

## Repository intent

- Treat the repository as the source of truth for OpenShift GitOps configuration.
- Preserve strict, schema-validated directory structure; avoid ad-hoc folders or file sprawl.
- Review architecture decisions in `docs/adr/` before proposing structural changes.

## Structure and deployment model

- `sources/<app-name>` is the primary deployment unit and must remain valid Argo CD source content.
- Organize configuration by application, not by delivery tool.
- Reuse the same `sources/<app-name>` for Argo CD, bootstrap Ansible, RHACM, and other delivery paths.
- `clusters/<clusterName>/<app>.yaml` gate files control where apps deploy and may include intentional Argo CD overrides.
- Keep default behavior in app-of-apps templates; use gate files for explicit deviations only.

## Governance model

- Every generated application belongs to an Argo CD AppProject.
- Every AppProject is owned by one or more LDAP-backed teams.
- Reflect team roles as OpenShift access levels: admins -> `admin`, developers -> `edit`, viewers -> `view`.
- Keep naming and ownership consistent with cluster, project, and app boundaries.

## Cluster and profile conventions

- Prefer cluster naming pattern `<dc>-<type>-<env>-<n>` unless explicitly using approved lab/personal exceptions.
- Model each cluster with exactly one cluster-type profile composed from reusable app-groups.
- Keep data-center, cluster-type, and environment metadata consistent for RHACM label-driven policy placement.

## Tooling conventions

- Use `oc` instead of `kubectl` for cluster interactions.
- Omit `startingCSV` in `sources/` subscriptions by default; pin only through explicit production overrides.
- Prefer consistency and derivability from repo structure over duplicate explicit configuration.
